@Leo Nice observation about the ones with the least variability.  However, I am not sure what you mean by "Tuesday has the biggest change daily" - change in what way - maximum temp, mimimum temp or average temp? And which cities show this biggest change the best.

As far as Fort Myers, what about the graph is making you think that it hsas hte most change?  Look at the information to the left of the graph to understand what the graph is showing in terms of forecast temps and actual temps. 

Keep on noticing and wondering.

@elle As you think about temperatures dipping below freezing, take a look at the city locations. Where are cities located that are dipping below freezing? Where are warmer cities located?

As far as global warming, is a 10 day temperature trend of cities in the United States in December enough data to conclude global warming all over the world?  There were some cities where the temperature fell over the course of the week.

Finally, if you are near one of the cities on the graph, how did the forecast for last Sunday - today compare to what actually happened.

@Eitan Prigan Thanks for your submission. When you compare regions, I recommend that you give an example or two of a city in the region that you are referencing.  For example, what mid America or East Coast city are on the higher end?  And you you mean higher end of the normal range of temperatures?

Did you notice anything about the variabilty in temperatures?  Which cities have high and low temperatures that are closer together and which cities have more variability in the difference between high and low temps?

I agree that weather and length of tourist season are related.

@Lily Rudolph thanks for sharing your thoughts.

When you say that cities such as Boston have varying temperatures or you saying they vary more compared to the normal highs and lows or compared to other cities?  Are their cities that have smaller differences between highs and lows? 

